04524nam a22008055i 9780813588506DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135885067 a10.36019/97808135885062doi  a(DE-B1597)526289  a(OCoLC)1020286182  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREL0000002bisacsh1 aIzzo, Amanda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aLiberal Christianity and Women's Global Activism :bThe YWCA of the USA and the Maryknoll Sisters /cAmanda Izzo. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (286 p.) :b16 black and white photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I. WOMEN AND CHRISTIAN FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY TWENTIETH CENTURY -- tPART II. FROM THE POPULAR FRONT AND AMERICAN CENTURY TO THE NEW FRONTIER -- tPART III "THE FERMENT OF FREEDOM" -- tEPILOGUE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligiously influenced social movements tend to be characterized as products of the conservative turn in Protestant and Catholic life in the latter part of the twentieth century, with women's mobilizations centering on defense of the "traditional" family. In Liberal Christianity and Women's Global Activism, Amanda L. Izzo argues that, contrary to this view, liberal wings of Christian churches have remained an instrumental presence in U.S. and transnational politics. Women have been at the forefront of such efforts. Focusing on the histories of two highly influential groups, the Young Women's Christian Association of the USA, an interdenominational Protestant organization, and the Maryknoll Sisters, a Roman Catholic religious order, Izzo offers new perspectives on the contributions of these women to transnational social movements, women's history, and religious studies, as she traces the connections between turn-of-the-century Christian women's reform culture and liberal and left-wing religious social movements of the 1960s and 1970s. Izzo suggests that shared ethical, theological, and institutional underpinnings can transcend denominational divides, and that strategies for social change often associated with secular feminism have ties to spiritually inspired social movements.      aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 4aYWCA. 4acatholic. 4acivil rights. 4aprotestant. 4asocial change. 4asocial progress. 4atraditional family. 4awomen's history. 4ayoung women's christian association. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Pilot eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311066330308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017-2018z978311065742508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2018z978311066608340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813588506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813588506.jpg  a978-3-11-065742-5  RUP eBook-Package 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066330-3  RUP Pilot eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-066608-3  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG